A comprehensive approach is followed in this study using data collected from a questionnaire (For more details about the questions and the results see the Appendix) and a literature review of the publicly available reports and studies. Both quantitative and qualitative data were collected on refugees across the three selected case studies, Iraq, Jordan, and Lebanon. These case studies were chosen according to these criteria:

                              1.

Location: The three countries are neighbors to Syria and have the most SRs besides Turkey (Fig. 1
                                 ). Moreover, they have a low-medium economy;


                              2.

Time: The camps in the three countries were established in the same period and last up to now;


                              3.

History: The three countries are Arab countries and have previous experience with refugees and displaced people;


                              4.

Context: The water sector in the three countries faces a severe shortage and various challenges, including large-scale migration, rapid urbanization, and uncontrolled increase of the population. Moreover, from 1960 to 2010, the rivers' flow in the three countries declined between 50 and 90%, and the agriculture sector consumes the majority of water in the region (90%) (Blue Peace Middle East, n.d.).

58.7% of Iraq respondents and 67.7% of Jordan respondents reported that they get their drinking water from the water network piped to the shelter, while 13.0% of Lebanon respondents reported the same. The same percentage (69.6%) reported having private water tanks filled by trucks paid for, either by them or by humanitarian organizations, compared to 29.1% and 41.3% in Jordan and Iraq. Yet 23,9%, 12.9% and 21.7% in Iraq, Jordan and Lebanon still using communal tanks and taps (see Fig. 2
                     ). Most respondents who do not have access to a network indicate that they spent less than 2 h daily to get their water needs (see Fig. 3
                     ).

Based on the above discussion, we recommend:

                           •

Integrating refugees into the host national plans is vital more than ever when it is related to the 2030 agenda both Targets 6.1 and 6.2 should be segregated by refugees, migrants and other vulnerable groups to ease the monitoring and evaluation process and make sure no one is left behind;


                           •

Promoting an enabling environment for refugees to be self-reliant and pursue a better life is a win-win situation for both refugees and their host. Refugee right to dignified work is important for the future sustainability of WASH services. Thinking beyond the humanitarian phase of the RC, WASH services should be handed over, delegated to a public or private service provider where implying tariffs that refugees can pay from their work guarantee the improvement and sustainability of the services;


                           •

Transit from a traditional linear WASH provision system to a sustainable and circular economy model in RCs because it is an advantage for both refugees and the host, it reduces the operational costs over time and raises awareness between donors, decision-makers, host governments, and all involved parties about the efficiency and effectiveness of shifting from humanitarian assistance to development and applying sustainable solutions from planning phase to have a well-organized master plan;


                           •

Partnership (SDG17) between different stakeholders including policymakers, humanitarian organizations, government and the private sector to promote sustainable WASH services. It would be useful to develop a sustainability partnership for emergencies at global and national levels with governments and water and sanitation authorities.
